tudy of the structure of fraud control in the welfare system by examining the relations between different levels of governmental agencies, from federal to local, and their enforcement practices. Policing Welfare shows how the enforcement regime of welfare has been constructed to further stigmatize those already living in poverty and deepens disparities of class, race, and gender in our society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aLaw enforcementzUnited States. 0aWelfare fraud investigationzUnited StatesvCase studies. 0aWelfare fraud investigationzUnited StatesxCase studies. 0aWelfare fraud investigationzUnited States. 0aWelfare fraudzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  awelfare, public assistance, social programs, government spending, budget, poverty, class, regulation, fraud, law enforcement, eligibility, governmental agencies, race, gender, stigma, oversight, nonfiction, history, sociology, politics, political science, criminology, legal system, punishment, waste, abuse, urban, administration, surveillance, dignity, policing, criminalization, inequality, inequity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073919008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226779539423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226779539/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-073919-0  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles